2.1

Learning Rate:

0.1: Epoch 12 is wehen Accuracy stabilized, after 20 loss does not get impacted either.

0.01: Changes less pronounced, seems to be growing at a small rate after 25 epochs.Seems to be less pronounced changes epoch to epoch.

0.001: Learns exceptionally slow, accuacy never higher than loss.

0.2 Extreme change between Epoxhs, loss was higher than accuracy in middle epochs

I think that between .01 and 1 is the best for this dataset and learning it. Anything lower takes much longer and would need large epochs and would use more energy, while anything higher allows for too much variaiton between epochs that prevents the model from being as precise and accurate.

2.2

The larger the batch size the less pronounced any epoch by epoch changes are, allowing a higher lr at the cost of a higher loss. This is because the larger batch size is closer to the gradient of the full data set. A lower batch size will have the opposite impact, having a larger distance between gradients in each epoch. This can be good becuase it can help from getting stuck on local minima. It does take longer to train, and a lower learning rate may be needed.

Question 3

Overflow problem: If an outlier is too large, $O_i$ > 1000 classically if you compare number of bedrooms to likelihood to buy a house, the probability becomes greater than 1 returning NaN.

Underflow: If the $O_i$ <-1000 the softmax underflows to 0, while this will not break the system, it causes all number except for the largest to fall to 0 and thus hurts gradient flow.

Subtracting the largest logit allows for $o_j - o_m$ to equal exp(0)=1, while all other $o_k <= 1$

This solution works well to help with overfitting but it does not help underfitting at all. There is also issues with finite precision, which may not matter in all cases. However certain cases require utmost accuracy, and have a low chance of high outliers.

Part 2

Question 1

Gradients vanishing within a sigmoid activaiton function is due to either a large positive or a large negative numbwer that after the function falls to either 1 or 0 respectively. $$ \sigma(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}} $$ and the derivative of this function is $$ \sigma'(x) = \sigma(x)(1 - \sigma(x)) $$ For example when x = 50 $$ \sigma'(50) = \sigma(50)(1 - \sigma(50)) \approx 0 $$ Since the derivative is effectively 0, the gradient provides effectively 0 loss changes.

Question 2:

Adding a hidden layer seems ot improve accuracy and seems to be effective at getting around local minima, at the cost of an increase in loss for the function. The second layer allows for the interpretation and allows the first layer to have non-linearity. Each layer adds onto the previous one and gets more specific. The first layer may just detect edges, while the second layer forms shapes and clusters, so on and so forth. However, like with training other models more hidden layers can lead to overfitting, as well as more computational power at progressively reduced effectiveness. A single neuron layer is useless, at is just employs a linear model, which is the problem that the multiple layers are supposed to solve in the first place. That is why a single neuron lauyer is fairly pointless.

Question 1

The number of epochs is a critical component in model training. As shown in the graphs above, the accuracy improved from 5 -> 10 -> 20 epochs. The attempt with 20 epochs is the only one with a higher accuracy than loss by the final epoch. It also has the highest accuracy at around 0.8 with the 10 epoch training being very close behind. The 10 epoch training is just meeting the threshold for loss to accuracy, and it can be considered an optimal place to stop if energy is the most important aspect.

Question 2

The ReLU and max-pooling changes improved the model by a large portion. Even from the onset there is a lower loss than accuracy, and the accuracy seems to start higher and not need to take any large jumps. It also seems like the updated method does not need as many epochs; with the improvements on accuracy as well leading to a much more efficient method energy consumption wise.
